Outfall 005A and 007A are municipal water; 006A (does not appear in my data) is river/seawater. All discharges in the yard would be from City of Bath water. No processes that use river water in the facility. Three sources take in river water not associated with an industrial process: 1) The Fire Pump on Pier 4 would use river water during an emergency. 2) The ships use some river water in the ballast tanks. 3) The Dry Dock will use river water during submergence in the ballast tanks.

Clam processing and packaging in Beals. During winter (Dec-Mar), wastewater goes to a septic system and is not discharged via outfall, but production in winter is also smaller (less than a third of summer production). So assuming 1/3 of year at 1/3 of production rate, infiltrated winter water is 1/6 of reported discharges, and reported discharges are 6/7 (~86%) of total water use.
SITESELECTION_NAICSDESCR: PREPARED FRESH OR FROZEN FISH AND SEAFOODS

We do not make snow at FKOC, we have enough natural snow to provide great skiing from Dec 15-May 1, we are very fortunate! We have made snow twice to support World Cup events at Lonesome Pine Trails and trucked it to our competition trails, that is the only time we made snow, and we really didn't need to, the IBU requested it to guarantee the event.

October 2, 2015 Expera terminated all pulp and papermaking. 2016 sources of waste water are primarily storm water, landfill leachate from the Juniper Ridge Landfill, waste water from the commercial LaBrees Bakery, filter backwash from the Orono-Veazie Water District and septage dewatering filtrate, leachate and storm water runoff from a composting facility. ND is current owner. As of 2024, mill under a period of extended downtime. Currently not pulling from the river, although under normal operation, we would. Main contributions to our wastewater process at this time are groundwater, stormwater and trucked-in wastewater from LaBrees Bakery and leachate from Juniper Ridge Landfill, as our wastewater treatment facility is still active.

Permit limit was 51MGD from October 2017 to March 2021. Three year mean for 2014 -2016 discharge flow averaged 31.9 MGD. 2017 fact sheet contains approximate flows from various internal uses. River is the only source of process and cooling water at the mill.  Municipal water from Town of Jay is used for restrooms and showers. Survey data is from 2020, the last year when the facility operated a pulp-manufacturing process. The facility will cease operation in April 2023. Actual municipal water consumption, as a percentage of total, is <0.5%, based on 2020 data.

SourceName: PRESUMPSCOT RIVER AND PORTLAND WATER DISTRICT SEBAGO LAKE
Description: Stopped withdrawing from the Presumpscot River around 1/20/2021. Portland Water District is now sole source of water. Outfall 001A is process water (volume reduced early 2021), 002A is filter backwash (not monitoried/reported in DEP data), 003A is surplus non-contact cooling water (eliminated early 2021). Total reported discharges in 2022 are ~5% of same in 2019, so assume public water was also 5% of earlier water use. To keep simple, apply same coefficients to all years, since post-2021 water use is much less significant (dropped by a factor of 10 to 20).

Various water balance numbers in 2013 permit indicate either 94,000 gpd water deliveries and 76,500 gpd of discharges (81.4% of deliveries) in text, or 59,500 gpd deliveries and 53,000 gpd of discharges (89.1% of deliveries) in flowchart Attachment B. Flowchart also indicates 5,500 gpd evaporative loss and 1,000 gpd to a septic tank. Actual reported discharges in 2019-2022 range 37,002-74,472 gpd and average 57,992 gpd. Survey reports 18% of deliveries discharged as wastewater, but I suspect the question was misinterpreted and 18 is the percent of deliveries NOT discharged as wastewater. Will use 82% to calculate my coefficient, as this is also close to the text of the 2013 permit.

FacilityName: TWIN RIVERS PAPER COMPANY MADAWASKA MILL
Description: Wastewater discharge exceeds river water intake due to recycled water sources within the mill that came from pulp carried over from mill in Edmundston NB. Storm water systems are fed to the wastewater treatment plant which also contribute to effluent discharge exceeding influent totals.
